Step 0 - Create Question2 folder. 
cd ~/Linux-Lab-Assignment
mkdir Question2
cd Question2

pwd

Step 1 - Create documentation files.
touch commands.txt output.txt explanation.txt
ls

Part 1 - 
Commands - 
mkdir ~/documents

Output - 
(no output)

Explanation - 
The mkdir command creates a directory named documents inside the home directory.

Part 2 - 
Commands -
cd ~/documents
touch plan.txt

Output -
(No output)
Explanation - 
cd moves into the documents directory and touch creates an empty file named plan.txt.

Part 3 - 
Commands -
echo "Finish Linux lab assignment by Friday" > plan.txt

Output -
(No output)
Explanation - 
This command writes sample project-related text into the plan.txt file.

Part 4 - 
Commands -
ls -l plan.txt

Explanation - 
ls -l displays file permissions, owner name, group name, size, and timestamp.

Part 5 - 
Commands -
cp plan.txt plan_copy.txt

Output -
(No output)
Explanation - 
The cp command creates a duplicate copy of plan.txt named plan_copy.txt.

Part 6 - 
Commands -
cd ~
mv documents project_documents

Output -
(No output)
Explanation - 
The mv command renames the documents directory to project_documents.

Part 7 - 
Commands -
mkdir ~/project_documents/archive

Output -
(No output) 
Explanation - 
This command creates an archive subdirectory inside project_documents.

Part 8 - 
Commands -
mv ~/project_documents/plan_copy.txt ~/project_documents/archive/

Explanation - 
The mv command moves plan_copy.txt into the archive directory.

Part 9 - 
Commands -
ls -R ~/project_documents

Explanation - 
ls -R displays the complete directory structure recursively.

Part 10 - 
Commands -
realpath ~/project_documents/archive/plan_copy.txt

Output -
/home/coder/project_documents/archive/plan_copy.txt
Explanation - 
realpath displays the absolute path of the specified file.




